#: src/async/10_resources.md:1
msgid "Loading Data with Resources"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:3
msgid ""
"Resources are reactive wrappers for asynchronous tasks, which allow you to "
"integrate an asynchronous `Future` into the synchronous reactive system."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:5
msgid ""
"They effectively allow you to load some async data, and then reactively "
"access it either synchronously or asynchronously. You can `.await` a "
"resource like an ordinary `Future`, and this will track it. But you can also "
"access a resource with `.get()` and other signal access methods, as if a "
"resource were a signal that returns `Some(T)` if it has resolved, and `None` "
"if it’s still pending."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:7
msgid ""
"Resources come in two primary flavors: `Resource` and `LocalResource`. If "
"you’re using server-side rendering (which this book will discuss later), you "
"should default to using `Resource`. If you’re using client-side rendering "
"with a `!Send` API (like many of the browser APIs), or if you are using SSR "
"but have some async task that can only be done on the browser (for example, "
"accessing an async browser API) then you should use `LocalResource`."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:9
msgid "Local Resources"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:11
msgid ""
"`LocalResource::new()` takes a single argument: a “fetcher” function that "
"returns a `Future`."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:13
msgid ""
"The `Future` can be an `async` block, the result of an `async fn` call, or "
"any other Rust `Future`. The function will work like a derived signal or the "
"other reactive closures that we’ve seen so far: you can read signals inside "
"it, and whenever the signal changes, the function will run again, creating a "
"new `Future` to run."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:16 src/async/10_resources.md:44
#: src/async/10_resources.md:99
msgid "// this count is our synchronous, local state\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:18
msgid ""
"// tracks `count`, and reloads by calling `load_data`\n"
"// whenever it changes\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:24
msgid ""
"Creating a resource immediately calls its fetcher and begins polling the "
"`Future`. Reading from a resource will return `None` until the async task "
"completes, at which point it will notify its subscribers, and now have "
"`Some(value)`."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:26
msgid ""
"You can also `.await` a resource. This might seem pointless—Why would you "
"create a wrapper around a `Future`, only to then `.await` it? We’ll see why "
"in the next chapter."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:28
msgid "Resources"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:30
msgid ""
"If you’re using SSR, you should be using `Resource` instead of "
"`LocalResource` in most cases."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:32
msgid ""
"This API is slightly different. `Resource::new()` takes two functions as its "
"arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:34
msgid ""
"a source function, which contains the “input.” This input is memoized, and "
"whenever its value changes, the fetcher will be called."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:35
msgid ""
"a fetcher function, which takes the data from the source function and "
"returns a `Future`"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:37
msgid ""
"Unlike a `LocalResource`, a `Resource` serializes its value from the server "
"to the client. Then, on the client, when first loading the page, the initial "
"value will be deserialized rather than the async task running again. This is "
"extremely important and very useful: It means that rather than waiting for "
"the client WASM bundle to load and begin running the application, data "
"loading begins on the server. (There will be more to say about this in later "
"chapters.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:39
msgid ""
"This is also why the API is split into two parts: signals in the _source_ "
"function are tracked, but signals in the _fetcher_ are untracked, because "
"this allows the resource to maintain reactivity without needing to run the "
"fetcher again during initial hydration on the client."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:41
msgid "Here’s the same example, using `Resource` instead of `LocalResource`"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:46
msgid "// our resource\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:50
msgid "// every time `count` changes, this will run\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:55
msgid ""
"Resources also provide a `refetch()` method that allows you to manually "
"reload the data (for example, in response to a button click)."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:57
msgid ""
"To create a resource that simply runs once, you can use `OnceResource`, "
"which simply takes a `Future`, and adds some optimizations that come from "
"knowing it will only load once."
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:63
msgid "Accessing Resources"
msgstr ""

#: src/async/10_resources.md:65
msgid ""
"Both `LocalResource` and `Resource` implement the various signal access "
"methods (`.read()`, `.with()`, `.get()`), but return `Option<T>` instead of "
"`T`; they will be `None` until the async data has loaded."
msgstr ""

